-- BP, Burberry, Total, Vivendi, Wendel: European Equity Preview
-- B y   T a r a   L a c h a p e l l e
-- 2010-11-16T05:00:01Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-15/bp-burberry-total-vivendi-wendel-european-equity-preview.html
The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in  European  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are from the previous close.  The  Stoxx Europe 600 Index  rose 0.8 percent to 272.36. The
 Stoxx 50 Index  advanced 0.8 percent to 2,603.31. The  Euro Stoxx
50 Index , a benchmark for nations using the euro, gained 0.9
percent to 2,848.45.  Acciona SA  (ANA SM): The Spanish construction company said
its nine-month net income dropped 3.3 percent to 101 million
euros ($137 million). The stock rose 1.3 percent to 59.06 euros.  BP Plc  (BP/ LN): Billionaire oil investor T. Boone Pickens
bought shares of BP Plc, the owner of the well that caused the
biggest offshore U.S. crude spill in history, and sold his
holdings in Transocean Ltd., which owned the drilling rig that
exploded, according to a regulatory filing. The shares rose 0.6
percent to 448.7 pence.  Burberry Group Plc  (BRBY LN): The U.K.’s largest luxury
retailer is scheduled to report first-half earnings. The company
may report net income of 64.5 million pounds according to the
average of 5 estimates compiled by Bloomberg. The shares rose
1.6 percent to 1,020 pence.  Eiffage SA  (FGR FP): Deutsche Bank AG is managing the sale
of a 1.9 percent stake in France’s third-largest construction
company in an accelerated offer, the German bank said in an e-
mailed statement, without identifying who commissioned the sale.
Shares rose 1.6 percent to 36.90 euros.  Endesa SA  (ELE SM): The utility controlled by Enel SpA
(ENEL IM) was raised to “hold” from “reduce” at Caja Madrid
Bolsa (ESN) by equity analyst Victor Peiro Perez. The 12-month
target price is €20.30 per share. Endesa’s stock rose 1 percent
to 19.77 euros.  Fonciere des Regions SA  (FDR FP): France’s second-largest
publicly traded office landlord said Chairman Charles Ruggieri
cut his stake in the company and will step down to be replaced
by Jean Laurent. Shares added 1.5 percent to 78.32 euros.  Iliad SA  (ILD FP): The broadband Internet provider setting
up France’s fourth mobile-phone network said third-quarter
revenue rose to 511.1 million euros from 486.7 million euros a
year earlier. Shares fell 0.9 percent to 78.22 euros.  Total SA  (FP FP): Europe’s third-biggest oil company is
5.24 percent owned by Deutsche Bank AG, according to France’s
financial markets regulator. Shares gained 0.8 percent to 39.77
euros.  Vivendi SA  (VIV FP): The owner of the world’s largest
video-games company posted third-quarter profit that surpassed
analysts’ estimates. The company confirmed its full-year
outlook. Shares added 1.5 percent to 20.50 euros.  Wendel  (MF FP): Europe’s third-largest publicly traded
private-equity firm had third-quarter revenue of 1.46 billion
euros, up 23 percent from year-earlier levels, the company said
in an e-mailed statement today. Shares gained 1.6 percent to
61.84 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Tara Lachapelle  in New York at 
 tlachapelle@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
